  "kind": "note",
  "title": "Easton: Colony",
  "body": "The city of Philippi was a Roman colony (Acts 16:12), i.e., a military settlement of Roman soldiers and citizens, planted there to keep in subjection a newly-conquered district. A colony was Rome in miniature, under Roman municipal law, but governed by military officers (praetors and lictors), not by proconsuls. It had an independent internal government, the jus Italicum; i.e., the privileges of Italian citizens.",
  "source": {
    "label": "Matthew Easton, Illustrated Bible Dictionary (1897)",
    "url": "/encyclopedia.html?ref=Colony",
